@node MAIN "PopSearch AmigaGuide Documentation"

@{b}PopSearch 0.4 BETA@{ub}
An rxMUI AREXX script for IBrowse, AWeb or Voyager.
By Robert Williams

Many web browsers on other platforms are sprouting dedicated "search" gadgets.
PopSearch brings similar functionality to Amiga browsers in the form of a
small pop-up window that can be assigned to a fast-link button, toolbar icon
or menu item. PopSearch allows you to enter search terms or paste them in from
the clipboard. It can be configured to use a variety of search engines.

@{" Installation " link "INSTALL"} - Check requirements and set-up the script in your browser.
@{"    Usage     " link "USAGE"} - Just in case you're wondering what that "Cancel" button does.
@{"    Prefs     " link "PREFS"} - How to add additional search engines to PopSearch's list.
@{"   Author     " link "AUTHOR"} - Where to send bug reports, comments and suggestions.

You're free to do what you like with PopSearch although I'd appreciate a copy
if you make any improvements to it. I'm sure it goes without saying but you
use it at your own risk, I make no representations as to its quality.

@endnode

@node USAGE "PopSearch - Usage"

@{b}Using PopSearch@{ub}

First assign the PopSearch.rexx macro to a toolbar button, fast link or menu
item in your web browser as described in the @{"install" link "INSTALL"} section.

In your browser click on the button or choose the menu item and the PopSearch
window appears, it has the following gadgets:

"Search for" - Enter the search terms, you can use any special codes the
		  	   selected search engine allows.

			   If you wish to re-use earlier search terms click the drop-down
			   button to the right of the text gadget to show a list of search
			   terms used in this session (since the computer was last rebooted).
			   Double click on a search term to insert it into the text gadget.
			   If required you can then edit the search term.

			   Note: Search terms are listed in the order they were used with the
			   most recent first. If you re-use a term already in the list it is
			   not duplicated and remains in its old position.

"< Paste" - Replaces the contents of the "Search for" gadget with the contents
		 	of the clipboard (only the first line is inserted, clipboard unit
		  	0 is used).

Search engine - Use this cycle gadget to select the search engine you wish to
				use for this search. You can add more search engine options
				by editing the @{"PopSearch.prefs" link "PREFS"} file.

"Make default" - Makes the currently selected search engine the default the next
		  		 time you run PopSearch.

"Search" - Loads the search results into the current browser window and closes the
		   PopSearch window.

"Cancel" - Closes the PopSearch window.

@endnode

@node INSTALL "PopSearch - Installation"

@{b}How to Install PopSearch@{ub}

@{u}Ensure you have all the requirements installed.@{uu}

PopSearch requires the following:
	RexxMast running - RexxMast is supplied with the operating system in the
					   Sys:Tools directory.
	rxMUI installed - http://web.tiscali.it/no-redirect-tiscali/amiga/
	rexxsupport.library installed - Should be included with the OS.
	rexxtricks.library installed - Aminet, util/rexx/RexxTricks_386.lha

If any of the required files are missing PopSearch should warn you with an
error requester when you try to run it.

@{u}Copy the files to the correct directories.@{uu}

Copy PopSearch.rexx to a directory of your choice, for example your browser's
AREXX scripts directory.

Copy PopSearch.prefs to your S: directory. If you would prefer to place this
file elsewhere change the prefs_file variable at the top of the PopSearch.rexx
script.

PopSearch.prefs contains the list of search engines PopSearch can use, you can
add your own favourite engines by editing the file. Take a look at the
@{"Preferences" link "PREFS"} section of this document for details.

@{u}Set-up your browser.@{uu}

PopSearch supports IBrowse, AWeb and Voyager. It can be launched from anywhere
your browser can launch an ARexx script. For example in IBrowse you can launch
it from a fast-link button, toolbar button or even a FAB-menu item.

IBrowse

Set the action to "ARexx" and choose "PopSearch.rexx" from the file selector
there is no need to add any arguments.

AWeb

Type "run" into the command gadget then type the path and filename of
"PopSearch.rexx" then add the argument AWEB at the end of the line, e.g.:

run Projects:programming/PopSearch/PopSearch.rexx AWEB 

Voyager

Set the action to "ARexx" and choose "PopSearch.rexx" from the file selector
then add the argument VOYAGER at the end of the line, e.g.:

Projects:programming/PopSearch/PopSearch.rexx VOYAGER
 
@endnode

@node PREFS "PopSearch - Preferences"

You can easily add new search engines to PopSearch's list. Currently this is
achieved by editing the PopSearch.prefs file, located by default in your S:
directory.

This is an ASCII text file which can be edited in a text editor - please note
that the editor must preserve tab characters. Unfortunately this means Editpad
and Ed supplied with the OS cannot be used. If URLs suddenly show up in the
PopSearch cycle gadget your editor has probably stripped out the tabs.

Each line of the prefs file contains the details of the search engine. There
are two mandatory fields and an optional marker for the default engine. Each
line is formatted as follows:

<name><tab><search url><tab><default flag>

name - This is the text that shows up in the cycle gadget, it can include spaces.

url - This is the URL that submits a search for this search engine. Replace the
	  search terms with the code "%s", this can appear at any point in the URL
	  and PopSearch will replace it with the terms you enter.

default flag - Enter "DEFAULT" for the search engine you want to be selected
			   when you start PopSearch.

Here is the contents of a typical PopSearch.prefs file:

Google	http://www.google.com/search?q=%s	DEFAULT
Teoma	http://s.teoma.com/search?q=%s
Aminet	http://us.aminet.net/aminet.cgi?string=%s

Note: PopSearch checks each line of the preferences file as it is loaded,
lines which do not match the correct format are discarded and don't appear
in the search engine cycle gadget. If you add a search engine to your file
and it doesn't appear in the list check the prefs file carefully for errors.

Finding the URL for a Search Engine

For most search engines figuring out the correct URL to use is quite easy.
Simply perform a search as normal, then look at the URL bar of your browser.
Usually it is quite easy to figure out where the search terms you entered are
slotted in. Try editing the terms in the URL string and check the search still
works. If it does there's every chance of this search engine working with
PopSearch.

All you need to do now is copy the URL from your browser into a new line in the
PopSearch.prefs file. Replace your test search terms with "%s" and add the name
of the engine at the start of the line followed by a tab.

Done!

@endnode

